Short Title: Drug-Free Zones/Unauthorized Public Camping. (Public)
Sponsors:
Referred to:
March 19, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO ESTABLISH DRUG-FREE HOMELESS SERVICE ZONES AND INCREASE
3 THE PUNISHMENT IMPOSED FOR COMMITTING CERTAIN DRUG OFFENSES IN
4 A DRUG-FREE HOMELESS SERVICE ZONE AND TO BAN UNAUTHORIZED
5 PUBLIC CAMPING OR SLEEPING IN THE STATE AND LOCAL GOVERNMENT
6 UNITS OF THE STATE.
7 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
8
9 DRUG-FREE HOMELESS SERVICE ZONES
10 SECTION 1.(a) This section shall be known as "The Drug-Free Homeless Service
11 Zones Act."
12 SECTION 1.(b) G.S. 90-95(e) reads as rewritten:
13 "(e) The prescribed punishment and degree of any offense under this Article shall be
14 subject to the following conditions, but the punishment for an offense may be increased only by
15 the maximum authorized under any one of the applicable conditions:
16 …
17 (8) Any person 21 years of age or older who commits an offense under
18 G.S. 90-95(a)(1) on property used for a child care center, or for an elementary
19 or secondary school or within 1,000 feet of the boundary of real property used
20 for a child care center, or for an elementary or secondary school shall be
21 punished as a Class E felon. For purposes of this subdivision, the transfer of
22 less than five grams of marijuana for no remuneration shall not constitute a
23 delivery in violation of G.S. 90-95(a)(1). For purposes of this subdivision, a
24 child care center is as defined in G.S. 110-86(3)a., and that is licensed by the
25 Secretary of the Department of Health and Human Services.
26 (8a) Any person who commits an offense under G.S. 90-95(a)(1) in a drug-free
27 homeless service zone is guilty of a Class E felony if the person knows or
28 reasonably should know that it is a drug-free homeless service zone. Any
29 operator of a facility-based service who intentionally allows a person to
30 commit an offense under G.S. 90-95(a)(1) in a drug-free homeless service
31 zone is guilty of a Class H felony. For purposes of this subdivision, the transfer
32 of less than five grams of marijuana for no remuneration shall not constitute a
33 delivery in violation of G.S. 90-95(a)(1). The following definitions apply in
34 this subdivision:
*H437-v-4*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 a. Drug-free homeless service zone. – The following areas related to a
2 facility-based service:
3 1. If the facility-based service does not provide the services
4 described in sub-sub-subdivision 2. of this sub-subdivision, the
5 exterior and interior of any building and any accompanying
6 grounds used by a facility-based service and the area within
7 100 feet of that building or its accompanying grounds, if at
8 least one sign is permanently affixed in a visible manner at the
9 exterior of the main entrance of the facility that identifies the
10 building and its accompanying grounds as a drug-free
11 homeless service zone. The presence of this sign shall raise a
12 presumption that the person committing the offense knows or
13 reasonably should know that it is a drug-free homeless service
14 zone.
15 2. If the facility-based service provides shelter or housing for
16 victims of domestic violence that may be endangered if the
17 purpose or location of the facility were to become known, the
18 interior of any building and any outdoor area that may only be
19 accessed by entering through the building used by a
20 facility-based service, if at least one sign is permanently
21 affixed in a visible manner inside the building and within 5 feet
22 of the main entrance of the facility that identifies the building
23 as a drug-free homeless service zone. The presence of this sign
24 shall raise a presumption that the person committing the
25 offense knows or reasonably should know that it is a drug-free
26 homeless service zone.
27 b. Facility-based service. – Any (i) emergency or temporary shelter,
28 transitional housing provider, or permanent supportive housing entity
29 that receives local, State, or federal funds for the purpose of providing
30 shelter to homeless persons or (ii) other entity or facility that receives
31 local, State, or federal funds and primarily provides treatment,
32 preventive care, or other services to homeless persons.
33 c. Operator. – A sole proprietorship, corporation, partnership, joint
34 venture, limited partnership, limited liability partnership, limited
35 liability company, or any other entity or business association, or
36 contractor or subcontractor of the same, that is the recipient of local,
37 State, or federal funds to use for the provision of a facility-based
38 service.
39 …."
40 SECTION 1.(c) This section becomes effective December 1, 2026, and applies to
41 offenses committed on or after that date.
42
43 UNAUTHORIZED PUBLIC CAMPING AND SLEEPING
44 SECTION 2.(a) Article 9 of Chapter 160D of the General Statutes is amended by
45 adding a new section to read:
46 "§ 160D-917. Camping in public spaces.
47 (a) For purposes of this section, the following definitions shall apply:
48 (1) Department. – The North Carolina Department of Labor.
49 (2) Public camping or sleeping. – Lodging or residing overnight in a temporary
50 outdoor habitation used as a dwelling or living space and evidenced by the
51 erection of a tent or other temporary shelter, the presence of bedding or
Page 2 House Bill 437-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 pillows, or the storage of personal belongings or lodging or residing overnight
2 in an outdoor space without a tent or other temporary shelter. The term does
3 not include (i) lodging or residing overnight in a motor vehicle that is
4 registered, insured, and located in a place where it may be lawfully used or
5 (ii) camping for recreational purposes on property designated for those
6 purposes.
7 (b) Except as provided in subsection (c) of this section, a local government may not
8 authorize or otherwise allow any person to regularly engage in public camping or sleeping on
9 any public property, including any public building or its grounds and any public right-of-way
10 under the jurisdiction of the local government.
11 (c) The governing board of a local government may, by majority vote, designate property
12 owned by the local government within its jurisdictional boundaries to be used for a continuous
13 period of no longer than one year for the purposes of public camping or sleeping. Except for a
14 local government on the Unit Assistance List prepared by the Local Government Commission,
15 the local government shall, in making the property designation, establish and maintain minimum
16 standards and procedures related to the designated property for the purposes of:
17 (1) Ensuring the safety and security of the designated property and the persons
18 lodging or residing on the designated property.
19 (2) Maintaining sanitation, which must, at a minimum, include providing access
20 to clean and operable restrooms and running water.
21 (3) Coordinating with the county health department to provide access to
22 behavioral health services, which must include substance abuse and mental
23 health treatment resources.
24 (4) Prohibiting illegal substance use and alcohol use on the designated property
25 and enforcing the prohibition against such use.
26 (d) The local government's designation of property under subsection (c) of this section
27 shall not become effective until the designated property is certified by the Department. To obtain
28 the certification, the local government shall submit a request to the Commissioner of Labor which
29 shall include documentation proving all of the following:
30 (1) There are not sufficient open beds in homeless shelters in the local
31 government for the homeless population of the local government.
32 (2) The designated property is not contiguous to property zoned for residential
33 use by the local government.
34 (3) The designated property would not adversely and materially affect the
35 property value or safety and security of other existing residential or
36 commercial property in the local government and would not negatively affect
37 the safety of children.
38 (4) The local government has developed a plan to satisfy the minimum standards
39 and procedures prescribed in subsection (c) of this section.
40 (e) Within 10 days after receipt of a request to certify a designated property, the
41 Department shall notify the local government of the date the request was received and of any
42 omissions or errors in the request. The Department shall certify the designated property within
43 45 days after receipt of a complete submission from the local government, and the designated
44 property shall be deemed certified on the forty-fifth day if the Department takes no action.
45 (f) Within 30 days after certification of a designated property by the Department, the
46 local government shall publish the minimum standards and procedures required by subsection
47 (c) of this section on the local government's website. The local government shall continue to
48 make the standards and procedures publicly available for as long as any local government
49 property remains designated under subsection (d) of this section.
50 (g) The Department may inspect any designated property at any time, and the Department
51 shall provide notice to the local government recommending closure of the designated property if
House Bill 437-Fourth Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 the requirements of this section are no longer satisfied. A local government shall publish any
2 notice recommending closure on the local government's website not later than five business days
3 after receipt of the notice.
4 (h) Any resident of the local government, any owner of a business located in the local
5 government, or the Attorney General may bring a civil action in any court of competent
6 jurisdiction against the local government to enjoin a violation of subsection (b) of this section. If
7 the resident or business owner prevails in a civil action, the court may award reasonable expenses
8 incurred in bringing the civil action, including court costs, reasonable attorneys' fees,
9 investigative costs, witness fees, and deposition costs. An application for an injunction under this
10 subsection shall be accompanied by an affidavit attesting to all of the following:
11 (1) The applicant has provided written notice of the alleged violation to the
12 governing board of the local government.
13 (2) The applicant has provided the local government with five business days to
14 cure the alleged violation.
15 (3) The local government has failed to take all reasonable actions within its
16 governmental powers to cure the alleged violation within five business days
17 after receiving written notice of the alleged violation from the applicant.
18 (i) This section does not apply during any time period in which:
19 (1) The Governor has declared a state of emergency pursuant to G.S. 166A-19.20.
20 (2) A local government has declared a state of emergency pursuant to
21 G.S. 166A-19.22."
22 SECTION 2.(b) No later than June 30, 2027, the Department of Labor shall adopt
23 the rules necessary to implement the provisions of this section.
24 SECTION 2.(c) Subsection (a) of this section becomes effective June 30, 2027. The
25 remainder of this section is effective when it becomes law.
26
27 EFFECTIVE DATE
28 SECTION 3. Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
29 law.
